To achieve your goal, you can create an HTML file with an embedded JavaScript function that takes user-entered data, performs the calculation, and then displays the result. Here is an example of how you could structure such a file:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Savings Plan Calculator</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h2>Savings Plan Balance Calculator</h2>
    <label for="apr">Annual Percentage Rate (APR) %:</label>
    <input type="number" id="apr" value="3">
    <br>
    <label for="monthlyPayment">Monthly Payment $:</label>
    <input type="number" id="monthlyPayment" value="150">
    <br>
    <button onclick="calculateSavings()">Calculate</button>
    <h3>Balance after 12 months: $<span id="result">0.00</span></h3>

<script>
    function calculateSavings() {
        let apr = parseFloat(document.getElementById('apr').value);
        let monthlyPayment = parseFloat(document.getElementById('monthlyPayment').value);
        let months = 12;

        // Convert APR to a monthly rate
        let monthlyRate = apr / 100 / 12;

        // Initialize balance
        let balance = 0;

        // Calculate balance after 12 months
        for (let i = 0; i < months; i++) {
            balance = (balance + monthlyPayment) * (1 + monthlyRate);
        }

        // Update the result on the webpage
        document.getElementById('result').textContent = balance.toFixed(2);
    }
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

This HTML file starts with input fields for the APR (Annual Percentage Rate) and the monthly payment amount. It also includes a button that, when clicked, runs the `calculateSavings()` JavaScript function.

The `calculateSavings()` function retrieves the APR and monthly payment values from the input fields, then uses these values (along with the assumption of 12 months and monthly compounding) to calculate the savings plan balance after 12 months. It calculates the balance using a loop that compounds interest each month.

Finally, it updates the displayed result with the calculated balance, rounded to two decimal places. The initial values for APR and monthly payment are set according to your parameters, but these can be adjusted by the user before calculation.
